From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Jul 2026 03:23:39 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 20/20] imap: download large messages in resumable chunks via
 partial FETCH
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Messages fetched on demand (download-on-demand path) are now downloaded
with a sequence of BODY.PEEK[]<offset.count> partial FETCHes (mandatory
IMAP4rev1, RFC 3501) instead of a single full-body FETCH:

- Chunks are appended to a staging file in the blobdir whose length is
  the resume offset; an interrupted download continues where it stopped,
  across reconnects and restarts. Chunk size doubles from 128 KiB to a
  4 MiB cap to amortize round-trip latency. Peak memory drops from
  O(message size) to O(chunk size).
- End of message is detected by a short/empty chunk, never RFC822.SIZE,
  which some servers misreport; the size is only used for the new
  DownloadProgress events.
- The staging name is keyed by (transport, folder hash, UIDVALIDITY,
  UID); on UIDVALIDITY change stale staging files are discarded, and
  housekeeping keeps staging files of pending downloads alive.
- The assembled message must carry the expected Message-ID, guarding
  against servers that reuse UIDs without bumping UIDVALIDITY; a
  mismatch sets DownloadState::Failure instead of retrying forever.
- Fallback for servers without working partial FETCH: async-imap
  terminates a FETCH stream at the tagged response without surfacing
  its NO/BAD status, so a rejection looks like an empty response — the
  empty case is disambiguated by re-probing the UID (message still
  there = partial FETCH refused). Chunked downloads are then disabled
  for the transport for the process lifetime, a one-time device message
  informs the user, and the previous full-body fetch is used instead.
  Responses with a wrong or missing range origin past the start of the
  message are treated the same way rather than guessed at; a server
  that ignores the range but returns the full message from the
  beginning is accepted silently.
- fetch_msgs_mutex is now held only around receive_imf instead of the
  whole (potentially long) download; a message delivered concurrently
  via another transport is detected as duplicate by receive_imf.

Includes tests for the chunk loop (adaptive sizing, resume, size lies,
origin validation, error paths preserving resume state), the staging
file lifecycle, UIDVALIDITY-change discarding, housekeeping GC and the
one-time fallback device message.

